\chapter{Noun cases/declensions}

The following pages have the cases/declensions of various nouns. For
some nouns, at least one of their cases appears in the Bhagavad
Giitaa.\\

Note: we use the convention that Case 8 is the vocative case. Not all
people follow this convention.\\

If you are trying to memorize cases, below are some tips:

\begin{itemize}

\item In the tables of cases, memorize by columns, not by rows. That
  is, first choose ``singular,'' ``dual,'' or ``plural,'' and then try
  to memorize all the cases for your choice.

\item First memorize the cases for ``dual.'' Often, for ``dual,'' the
  (eight) cases have the following pattern: A, A, B, B, B, C, C, A
  (but the last A could be a D). Sometimes, the B's end with ``bhyaam
  = {\dn bhyaam},'' and the C's end with ``o.h = {\dn o.h}.''

\item Sometimes, male nouns and neuter nouns share many
  cases. Sometimes the only differences appear in Case 1 (nominative)
  and Case 2 (accusative).

\item Sometimes, neuter nouns have the same cases for Case 1
  (nominative) and Case 2 (accusative).

\item Sometimes, Case 8 (vocative) is the same as (or very similar to)
  Case 1 (nominative).

\item Sometimes, noun roots which end with ``u'' have ``v'' in some of
  their cases.

\item Sometimes, cases seem to follow a pattern, regardless of the
  gender of the noun, or other factors. For example, a case which ends
  with ``.su = {\dn .su}'' or ``su = {\dn su}'' might be Case 7
  (locative) plural, which means ``at/in/on things.''

\item Sometimes, a case has an ``n = {\dn n}'' sound near the end. But
  if there is an ``r = {\dn r}'' sound before the ``n'' and near it,
  the ``n'' might become retroflex: .n = {\dn .n}. Presumably, the
  retroflex sound is easier to pronounce because the tongue is already
  near the back of the mouth for the ``r'' sound.

\item Sometimes, people write ``s = {\dn s}'' instead of ``.h = {\dn
  .h}''. For example: karma.nas = {\dn karma.nas} = karma.na.h = {\dn
  karma.na.h} = of/at/in/on action.

\end{itemize}
